		<header>
			
			<h1>PACP reiterate concerns over progress in EPA negotiations while trade policy reforms proceed </h1>

			
			<h4>
												16 July 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>On 11 May 2012, the ministers of the Pacific bloc of the ACP grouping issued a press statement urging the EC to provide ‘its formal written comments on the draft legal text, the development cooperation chapter, and the market access offers that were submitted by the Pacific ACP region in July 2011’.</p><p>This package of proposals agreed by the Pacific states included the market access offers of eight Pacific ACP (PACP) governments, as well as revised legal texts on contentious issues and the development cooperation chapter. According to the lead spokesperson of the Pacific ACP ministers, ‘the onus is now firmly on the European Commission to increase the level of engagement with the Pacific to conclude negotiations by 2012.’</p><p>According to the press statement, ‘the last formal, face-to-face negotiation session [...] was in 2009’, although ‘other ACP regions have had numerous meetings with the EC at various levels’ since then. The statement reiterated the commitment of PACP governments to ‘conclude a development friendly EPA that will contribute towards addressing the unique trade needs and challenges of the Pacific’.</p><p>This position was reiterated at the meeting of the ACP Council of Ministers in June 2012 in Vanuatu, with emphasis being placed on the importance of fully accommodating the geographical and structural constraints on PACP economies. The view was expressed that ‘the interim EPA as it currently stands does not satisfactorily address these fundamental considerations.’</p><p>In terms of broader issues to be addressed, the Prime minister of Vanuatu called at the joint ACP–EU Council of Ministers’ meeting for the EU to lift its current ban on kava exports to the EU.</p><p>As PACP governments conduct international negotiations, many are also developing their own trade policy. In May 2012, the government of the Marshall Islands announced the adoption of its first Trade Policy Framework, which aims to mainstream trade into the national development plan and to ‘undertake the necessary reforms in trade and investment laws to create a transparent and predictable environment, which is conducive for sustainable, inclusive and private sector-led economic growth and development’. The policy ‘proposes bold reforms including liberalisation of a number of sectors, to improve the basic infrastructure services such as transportation, telecommunication and education’. It also proposes ‘the introduction of a consumption tax’ to enable the Marshall Islands ‘to participate in various trade agreements including the Pacific Island Countries’ Trade Agreement (PICTA), PACER-Plus and an EPA’. The Trade Policy Framework specifically recommends signing the comprehensive EPA with the EU to facilitate value-added processing in the fisheries sector. The Framework also identifies the trade and development needs of the Marshall Islands and associated ‘aid for trade’ needs.</p><p>Also in May 2012, Pacific Island Forum trade ministers discussed a possible trade agreement with the US. PACP governments stressed that they were seeking a ‘preferential, non-reciprocal development-orientated broader trade and economic agreement with the USA’. In view of capacity constraints, the ministers underlined the importance of ensuring that new trade negotiations did not compromise ‘current regional integration initiatives’, and directed the Forum Secretariat to formulate a strategy for the negotiations to be approved at Ministerial level.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
