				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>PACP governments continue to express their preference for non-reciprocal trade agreements as they await a response from the EC to their July 2011 proposals. In February 2012, at a joint Trade Committee meeting with Papua New Guinea, EC representatives highlighted the practical difficulties faced in pursuing comprehensive EPA negotiations simultaneously at the national and regional levels. These difficulties may in part account for the delay in the preparation of a formal EC response to the regional proposals tabled in July 2011. Nevertheless, the delays need to be seen against the background of the EC’s September 2011 proposal to reform market access regulation no. 1528/2007, with the deadline of 1 January 2014 for the completion of the EPA process.</p><p>The adoption of the Marshall Islands Trade Policy Framework is indicative of the efforts in the Pacific region to get to grips with trade policy reform challenges. The framework is designed not only to provide a basis for concluding the EPA process, but also to develop trade relations with a wider range of trade partners, reflecting the shifting focus of global economic growth.</p>
		</div>
		
